[2] Cholera - Sierra Leone
Date: Tue, 31 Aug 2004
From: Alfonso Rodriguez <ajrm_msds@yahoo.es>
Source: Yahoo News, UK & Ireland / AFP [edited]
<http://uk.news.yahoo.com/040831/323/f1mno.html>

Death toll from Sierra Leone cholera outbreak rises to 53
--------------------------------------------------
A new outbreak of cholera is continuing to claim lives in Sierra Leone,
health officials said, with the death toll rising to 53 from a total of
some 531 cases.
Torrential rains have overwhelmed the war-ravaged west African state's
already decrepit sanitation system, sending raw sewage seeping into the
streets of the capital, Freetown. The city has become an incubator for the
water-borne bacterial disease, which manifests itself through diarrhea and
severe dehydration, one hygienist told AFP on condition of anonymity.
Doctors are blaming the "unhygienic practices" of most people, imploring
them to wash their hands after using the toilet and to take greater care in
preparing and handling food. "The situation is further aggravated by many
traders ignoring warnings to cover food displayed to the public," the
hygienist said.
Initially confined to the Freetown area, particularly the eastern Rokupa
district, the outbreak has spread to Yeliboya, an archipelago nestled in
the Atlantic Ocean near Guinea, local media reported.
Though there had been no cholera in Sierra Leone for the past 4 years, the
15 islands that make up Yeliboya are regularly infected with the disease
due to poor sanitation.
