[5] Cholera - India (Kashmir)
Date: Tue, 31 Sep 2004
From: ProMED-mail promed@promedmail.org
Source: New Kerala.com [edited]
<http://news.newkerala.com/health-news-india/index.php?action=fullnews&id=10408>

A cholera scare has gripped Jammu and Kashmir. Amid fears over the quality
of drinking water supplies in the state, people in some rural areas have
reportedly been affected by cholera. As many as 24 people have been
admitted with cholera-like complaints to a hospital here and at least one
of them, a woman, has tested positive for _Vibrio cholerae_, the bacteria
responsible for spreading the disease.
The issue has rocked the state assembly. Chief Minister Mufti Muhammad
Sayeed blamed the media for indulging in "yellow journalism" by carrying
sensational stories about a cholera scare that he said had no basis. But to
Sayeed's embarrassment, the positive cholera test was carried out by the
government-run medical college in Srinagar. Kashmir has earlier been hit by
cholera epidemics that have killed many. With better healthcare and safe
drinking water, locals had forgotten the scourge. But it now seems the
disease could re-visit the Kashmir Valley unless the health department and
the people act fast.
"The problem could be really serious in rural areas where people relieve
themselves in the open. Human feces from an infected person could get into
rivers and other water sources as toilets in villages are usually built
close to water sources," said Pervaiz Koul, a doctor. Kashmir's best-known
gastroenterologist, Muhammad Sultan Khuroo, expressed similar views.
"Cholera invariably spreads through water contaminated with human feces in
the initial stage. Edible items, fluids and linen contamination may spread
the infection secondarily," Khuroo said. "I don't know whether the patients
consumed tap water or some other water, but it must have been highly
contaminated with human excreta," Khuroo said. He also suspected that the
disease might have reached the Kashmir Valley through laborers who came
from other states.
