[6] Cholera - India (Kashmir)
Date: Sun, 29 Aug 2004
From: ProMED-mail <promed@promedmail.org>
Source: Hindustan Times [edited]
<http://www.hindustantimes.com/news/5922_975961,0015002000000116.htm>

Watery diarrhea: Srinagar on red alert
--------------------------------------
Amid reports of "watery diarrhea" spreading in many pockets of Srinagar, a
red alert has been sounded in all the city hospitals. The doctors and
paramedical staff have been instructed to take precautionary measures while
treating such patients.
During the last 3 days, more than 150 patients suffering from dysentery,
vomiting and severe dehydration have been treated in SMHS and Valley's
premier hospital, SKIMS. Many patients, mostly from the city suburbs, are
still admitted in the hospitals.
A 50-year-old woman from Kawadara pocket of the summer capital died and
doctors who treated her confirmed that she died of cholera. "This is the
only confirmed case of cholera death. Most of the other patients admitted
in different are hospitals are suffering from gastroenteritis," said a
doctor at SKIMS.
In fact, it was only after the death on Thu, 26 Aug 2004, that an alert was
sounded in Srinagar hospital. "After the death, a meeting of department of
emergency medicines, gastroenterology, nephrology, microbiology, nursing
administration and hospital management was called by the authorities,"
disclosed Dr Syed Amin Tabish, medical administrator of SKIMS. "We have to
be alert, but there is no need for any panic," he said, adding that Ward 2A
of the hospital was vacated from the indoor patients, as those suffering
from gastroenteritis are now admitted in the ward. He termed this disease
as 'watery diarrhea'.
"Recently, we have marked an increase in the number of patients who have
gastroenteritis which follows a refractory course. All precautionary
measures have been taken which include immediate isolation of the patient,
intravenous fluid, antibiotics, investigations, including cultures and
transporting culture media," remarked Dr Syed Zafferullah, a senior
resident at SKIMS.
Senior doctors believe that the disease had been transmitted through
"contaminated" drinking water. "The source of its outbreak is water and we
advise people to consume only boiled water," said Dr Tabiash, adding that
they had constituted a team of microbiologists to examine the quality of
water from the localities from which reports of disease had come.
[Byline: Majid Jahangir]
