[7] Cholera, lake isolate - USA (Texas)
Date: Tue, 31 Aug 2004
From: ProMED-mail <promed@promedmail.org>
Source: El Paso Times [edited]
<http://www.borderlandnews.com/stories/borderland/20040831-162826.shtml>

Borderland in brief: Cholera-like germ is in Ascarate Lake water
--------------------------------------------------
Bacteria that can cause diarrhea has been found in Ascarate Lake, prompting
health officials to caution people not to water ski on the lake, allow its
water to enter cuts or eat fish from the lake without cooking it properly.
The _Vibrio cholerae_ germ, a non-01 type, is "not the toxic bad one that
we worry about becoming a cholera epidemic," said Dr. Jose Magana, director
of the City-County Health and Environmental District. The contamination
resulted from runoff of pollutants after rain combined with warm weather,
he said. Drier weather and cooler temperatures should stop the problem.
[Non 0-1 (and Non O-139) _V. cholerae_ isolates do cause less severe
disease and are not uncommonly associated with cases along the Gulf Coast
of the USA. Cases, however, have been documented associated with shellfish
in New England. - Mod.LL]
